    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided text, here is the breakdown of share-based compensation expense by segment, the availability of data by type, and an analysis of whether it constitutes a real economic cost.\n\n### 1. Share-Based Compensation Expense Breakdown by Segment\nThe text provides the following segment-level share-based compensation expenses across multiple periods:\n\n| Period | Space | Connectivity | AI | Total Reportable Segments |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Three Months Ended Mar 31, 2026** | $145 million | $116 million | $378 million | **$639 million** |\n| **Three Months Ended Mar 31, 2025** | $108 million | $75 million | $49 million | **$232 million** |\n| **Year Ended Dec 31, 2025** | $515 million | $369 million | $1,063 million | **$1,947 million** |\n| **Year Ended Dec 31, 2024** | $472 million | $296 million | $16 million | **$784 million** |\n\n*(Note: The text also breaks down the total expense by **financial statement line item**. For example, in FY 2025, the $1,947 million total was allocated as: $253M to Cost of Revenue, $859M to R&D, and $835M to SG&A).*\n\n### 2. Breakdown by Type (RSUs, Stock Options, etc.)\n**The provided text does not contain a breakdown of the recognized income statement *expense* by award type** (i.e., it does not state how much of the expense came from RSUs vs. Stock Options vs. ESPPs). \n\nHowever, the text does confirm the **types of equity awards** the company utilizes and provides valuation metrics for them:\n*   **Stock Options:** Valued using the Black-Scholes model (or Monte Carlo for the CEO). The text notes the weighted-average grant-date fair values and the total intrinsic value of options exercised (e.g., $1,249 million in FY 2025).\n*   **RSUs (Restricted Stock Units) & RSAs (Restricted Stock Awards):** Valued based on the fair market value of the common stock on the grant date. \n*   **ESPP (Employee Share Purchase Plan):** Valued on the offering date.\n*   **Performance-Based CEO Awards:** (e.g., the "xAI Award", "SpaceX CEO Award", and "AI CEO Award") Valued using a Monte Carlo simulation model due to complex market, service, and performance conditions.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Is Share-Based Compensation a "Real" Economic Cost?\n**Yes, share-based compensation (SBC) is absolutely a real economic cost**, even though it is classified as a **non-cash expense** on the cash flow statement. \n\nHere is why financial analysts and economists consider it a real cost:\n\n*   **Wealth Transfer and Dilution:** When a company pays employees with equity (or the right to buy equity at a discount), it is transferring wealth from existing shareholders to employees. If the company issues new shares to fulfill RSUs or option exercises, existing shareholders suffer **dilution** (their slice of the ownership pie shrinks, reducing Earnings Per Share). If the company buys back shares on the open market to offset this dilution, it incurs a massive, direct **cash cost**.\n*   **Opportunity Cost:** Equity has value. If the company did not give those shares or options to employees, it could have issued them to outside investors in exchange for cash, or retained the equity for future strategic use. Giving it away for labor means forgoing that alternative cash value.\n*   **The "Cash Substitution" Reality:** SBC is simply a substitute for cash compensation. If a company stopped granting RSUs and options, it would have to pay its engineers and executives significantly higher cash salaries and bonuses to remain competitive in the labor market. Therefore, SBC represents real labor costs incurred to generate revenue.\n*   **Accounting Standards (GAAP/IFRS):** As noted in the text (referencing FASB ASC Topic 718), accounting standards require SBC to be recorded as an expense on the income statement. The matching principle dictates that if labor helps generate revenue in a given period, the cost of that labor (whether paid in cash or stock) must be expensed in that same period to reflect true profitability.\n\n**Why do companies add it back to "Adjusted EBITDA"?**\nIn the provided text, the company adds SBC back to Income from Operations to calculate *Segment Adjusted EBITDA*. Companies do this because SBC does not require an immediate outlay of cash from the corporate treasury, and they argue it is a non-operating or non-core metric. However, investors heavily scrutinize this add-back; ignoring SBC can artificially inflate a company\'s operational performance and mask the true economic cost of retaining talent.',
