d overhead) as well as capitalized launch costs incurred by the Space segment to get them to orbit.\n* **AI Segment:**\n  * **Data Center Infrastructure:** Significant long-term construction projects and AI infrastructure (which also incurs capitalized interest during construction).\n  * **Servers and Networking Equipment:** Hardware supporting AI computational needs.\n* **General / Cross-Segment Assets:**\n  * Machinery and equipment, buildings and improvements, and leasehold improvements utilized across corporate and operational functions.\n\n---\n\n### 3. What is the Useful Life of the Assets?\nThe company uses the straight-line method for most assets, except for flight vehicles which are depreciated based on usage (flights). \n\n**Property, Plant, and Equipment (Tangible Assets)**\n| Asset Classification | Estimated Useful Life |\n| :--- | :--- |\n| **Flight vehicle hardware** | 5 - 25 flights *(based on expected average flights, recovery/refurbishment success, and economic feasibility)* |\n| **Satellites** | 3 - 5 years *(Specifically: 5 years for broadband satellites; 3 years for first-generation mobile satellites)* |\n| **Servers and networking equipment** | 5 - 6 years |\n| **Data center infrastructure** | 20 - 25 years |\n| **Launch sites** | 7 - 20 years |\n| **Machinery and equipment** | 3 - 10 years |\n| **Buildings and improvements** | 30 years |\n| **Leasehold improvements** | Shorter of 7 - 20 years or the life of the lease |\n\n**Finite-Lived Intangible Assets (Amortization)**\n| Intangible Asset Classification | Weighted-Average Useful Life |\n| :--- | :--- |\n| **User base** | 9.0 years |\n| **Brand** | 5.0 years |\n| **Advertising customer relationships** | 5.0 years |\n| **Existing technology** | 3.0 - 3.2 years |\n| **Acquired workforce** | 2.0 years |',
